Stages of the development of soybean seeds and embryo.
Zero days post flowering, zygote has formed and the primary endosperm is multinucleated.
One day post flowering, embryo has undergone a cell division. Endosperm has formed a number of nuclei.
Two days post flowering, embryo has reached 4 to 8 cells.
Three days post flowering, pro-embryo is fully differentiated from suspensor. Endosperm has formed a peripheral layer and has a central vacuole.

Four to five days post flowering, the embryo is spherical with a protoderm and developed suspensor. Endosperm surrounds the embryo and is cellular proximal to the embryo but is acellular distal to the embryo.
column4: Globular stage NARROW; PO:0001185 C globular stage NARROW

column3: Cotyledons begin development and are just visible six to 7 days post flowering.
Ten to 14 days post flowering, cotyledons are in their normal position. Primary leaf primordia is visible and the endosperm occupies approximately 1/2 of the seed volume.
column4: PO:0001078 E expanded cotyledon stage BROAD

column3: Cotyledons have reached final size and the primordia of the 1st trifoliolate has formed 20 to 30 days post flowering. Endosperm is almost completely assimilated.
column4: PO:0001081 F mature embryo stage NARROW

column3: Thirty to 50 days post flowering endosperm is absent and the seed size is increasing.
Fifty to 80 days post flowering, seed weight and size has increased to about half mature size and weight.
Eighty to 110 days post flowering, seed has obtained mature size. Seed weight begins to drop due to dessication.

Elongated absorptive cells formed from root epidermal cells.
Spherical structures formed by swelling of the root cortex. Swelling is caused by colonization of a root hair by members of the bacterial genus Rhizobium.

column2: Light energy absorbed per reaction center (ABS/RC)
column3: Commonly referred to as ABS/RC. It is the average energy absorption by chlorophyll molecules per active reaction center. Can be calculated as (TRo/RC)/(TRo/ABS) where TRo is the the maximal rate by which an excitation is trapped by the RC resulting in the reduction of Qa.
The quantum yield of the electron transport flux from Qa to Qb, defined as electron transport from Qa to Qb divided by the light absorption (ABS) of the photo-centers.

column2: Probability a trapped excitation moves an electron beyond Qa- (ETo/TRo)
